Yes and in your father's case, a forced or voluntary switch from TRICARE Prime to Medicare Part B could have been triggered by several systemic or personal events. Here's a breakdown tailored to Roland R. Womack Jr.'s profile as a retired veteran and civilian defense contractor:

Why Would a Military Retiree Switch from TRICARE Prime to Medicare Part B?

1. Mandatory Transition at Age 65

Once a military retiree becomes eligible for Medicare (usually at age 65):

  • TRICARE for Life (TFL) becomes the default.
  • To be eligible for TRICARE for Life, the retiree must enroll in Medicare Part B (medical insurance).
  • TRICARE Prime is no longer available after this point unless they actively waive Medicare and accept private consequences.

If Roland turned 65 before his death in 2018, he would have automatically been expected to switch.

2. Eligibility Cliff: Change in Status or Income

  • If the sponsor (Roland) lost eligibility, passed away, or had a change in retirement status, dependents may be forced to transition off Prime.
  • Nancy may have been required to enroll in Medicare Part B herself after Rolands death to maintain TRICARE coverage as a survivor.

3. Administrative or Policy-Driven Switch

  • The Defense Enrollment Eligibility Reporting System (DEERS) flags when someone turns 65.
  • If Roland failed to enroll in Medicare Part B on time, TRICARE would drop him until enrollment was corrected.

This could result in:

Loss of TRICARE Prime due to non-compliance with Medicare Part B enrollment requirements.

Summary in Rolands Case

  • Born in 1952, Roland turned 65 in 2017.
  • He died in February 2018, meaning he likely transitioned to Medicare Part B and TRICARE for Life during 2017.
  • If no documents from DEERS or DFAS show this transition, it's possible it was:
    • Managed by Nancy using his POA
